  "text": "Comparison with previous reports of rotavirus-induced responses. Rotavirus infection induces profound alterations in the morphology and biochemistry of the host cell; however, the molecular mechanisms underlying these events are not fully understood. Previous work in MA104 cells demonstrated an upregulation, at the mRNA and protein level, of BiP (grp78) [CITATION_1] . Some genes are grouped according to related biological function. *, Genes whose transcriptional level changed more than twofold in all three experimental hybridizations (see Table 1 ).",
